        <descriptionSet>
            <description>The transcontinental Canadian Pacific Railway and great hotels the firm built changed how people saw the mountains. Once considered a barrier to progress, the mountains were now viewed by many as a major tourist attraction. Canadian Pacific Railway’s Glacier House Hotel opened near the glacier’s terminus in 1885. From the Swiss Guides working at the hotel to the photo exhibits and books, Glacier National Park mountains were promoted. Scientists like William H. Sherzer studied glaciers in British Columbia, describing their rich varied colors, were published in 1904 as a Smithsonian Expedition. The glacier’s name means “big water” in the Okangan language.</description>
